descript.abstract: Canada Provinces represents the Canadian provinces and territories as well as coastline, international boundaries, provincial boundaries, and demographics. The boundaries are digitized from CanMap®.
descript.purpose: Canada Provinces provides the provinces and territories of Canada with detail appropriate for national, regional, and local levels.
descript.supplinf: Largest scale when displaying the data: 1:50,000.

citeinfo.title: Canadian Data Bundle–Data sets from CanMap with source scales of 1:2000 to 1:50,000.

procstep.procdesc:
The data set is a fully georeferenced, purely digital product. The boundaries are digitized from CanMap. Source data ranges from municipal mapping at a very large scale of 1:2,000 or larger, to a medium scale of 1:50,000 scale from NTDB*. Source time period of content ranges from a few to several years (as in the case of NTDB*).
*NTDB is the National Topographic Data Base, developed and maintained by Natural Resources Canada.

The following steps were performed by ESRI for Data & Maps 2002: removed erroneous island at 80 N 135 W, changed "Newfoundland" to "Newfoundland and Labrador", and deleted sliver polygons.
The following steps were performed by ESRI: Extracted data set from DMTI Spatial Canadian Data Bundle. Reduced the width of Name attribute. Added Area attribute calculating its values in square kilometers. Added Fips_admin attribute from FIPS 10-4 tables. Added Pop1996 and Dwell1996 attributes aggregating their values from Canada Municipalities. Created ArcGIS™ layer file (.lyr). Created ArcView legend file (.avl). Created projection file (.prj). Ran ArcView Avenue request ExportClean, and created spatial indices.

horizpa.horizpar: The positional accuracy ranges from sub-meter (GPS derived) to 5 meters (1:50,000 National Topographic Data Base (NTDB) areas) or greater, in the case of Northern areas in Canada not covered by NTDB, namely, most of Nunavut, much of Northwest Territories and northern parts of British Columbia, Alberta, Manitoba, Ontario and Quebec.
